## Functions

### LLVMBinaryCopyMemoryBuffer() {#gaeff7af5e130db7b11a27ed233f57d5c6}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>LLVMMemoryBufferRef LLVMBinaryCopyMemoryBuffer (<a href="/docs/api/groups/llvmcsupporttypes/#ga7b146c3251529961e8eeda888adac209">LLVMBinaryRef</a> BR)</>}>
Retrieves a copy of the memory buffer associated with this object file.

The returned buffer is merely a shallow copy and does not own the actual backing buffer of the binary. Nevertheless, it is the responsibility of the caller to free it with <code>LLVMDisposeMemoryBuffer</code>.


<SectionUser title="See Also">
llvm::object::getMemoryBufferRef
</SectionUser>

### LLVMCreateBinary() {#gabe1e0252c6f4bc1b0b1b8b06f9df3546}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>LLVMBinaryRef LLVMCreateBinary (<a href="/docs/api/groups/llvmcsupporttypes/#ga9867eaa7b17ba17405cdf2539bedb108">LLVMMemoryBufferRef</a> MemBuf, <a href="/docs/api/groups/llvmcsupporttypes/#ga9c43e01525516ff6b4feab5166c5b1da">LLVMContextRef</a> Context, char &#42;&#42; ErrorMessage)</>}>
Create a binary file from the given memory buffer.

The exact type of the binary file will be inferred automatically, and the appropriate implementation selected. The context may be NULL except if the resulting file is an LLVM IR file.

The memory buffer is not consumed by this function. It is the responsibilty of the caller to free it with <code>LLVMDisposeMemoryBuffer</code>.

If NULL is returned, the <code>ErrorMessage</code> parameter is populated with the error&#39;s description. It is then the caller&#39;s responsibility to free this message by calling <code>LLVMDisposeMessage</code>.

### LLVMObjectFileCopySectionIterator() {#gabb7cdf8752b1939d369936207f9b25c1}

  prototype={<>LLVMSectionIteratorRef LLVMObjectFileCopySectionIterator (<a href="/docs/api/groups/llvmcsupporttypes/#ga7b146c3251529961e8eeda888adac209">LLVMBinaryRef</a> BR)</>}>
Retrieve a copy of the section iterator for this object file.

If there are no sections, the result is NULL.

The returned iterator is merely a shallow copy. Nevertheless, it is the responsibility of the caller to free it with <code>LLVMDisposeSectionIterator</code>.
